CatDescriptText: Cutline of image published in New Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, May 2, 1970, pg. 1, reads: "Pittsburgh Panther Posters - Highly visible evidence that the Black Panther Party and all of its workings have entered the Pittsburgh scene can be witnessed in Homewood not only by the opening of two meals-for-school youngster projects, a Homewood-Brushton office for a Panther wing, and an organizing drive, but also by these large full-newspaper-size wall posters of the Black Community News Service plastered abundantly on store windows in the Homewood-Brushton area, plus distribution of campaign buttons reading 'Free Huey' and other Panther slogans."
TitMainTitle: Broadside for Black Panther Manifesto on trial of Bobby Seale, pasted on window in Homewood
